04004nam a22006375i 9780226576404DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018016687  a9780226576404  a(DE-B1597)524940  a(OCoLC)1053888333  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPR468.A56bK73 2018 4aPR468.A56bK73 2019 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a823.8093622231 aKreilkamp, Ivan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMinor Creatures :bPersons, Animals, and the Victorian Novel /cIvan Kreilkamp. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b6 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAnimal Lives00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tChapter One. Home, Animal, Novel -- tChapter Two. Petted Things: Cruelty and Sympathy in the Brontës -- tChapter Three. Dying like a Dog in Dickens -- tChapter Four. Middlemarch’s Brute Life -- tChapter Five. Using and Pitying Animals in Thomas Hardy -- tChapter Six. Tracking Animal Agency in Conan Doyle and Hardy -- tChapter Seven. “Infinite Compassion”: Nonhuman Life in Schreiner’s The Story of an African Farm -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the nineteenth century, richly-drawn social fiction became one of England’s major cultural exports. At the same time, a surprising companion came to stand alongside the novel as a key embodiment of British identity: the domesticated pet. In works by authors from the Brontës to Eliot, from Dickens to Hardy, animals appeared as markers of domestic coziness and familial kindness. Yet for all their supposed significance, the animals in nineteenth-century fiction were never granted the same fullness of character or consciousness as their human masters: they remain secondary figures. Minor Creatures re-examines a slew of literary classics to show how Victorian notions of domesticity, sympathy, and individuality were shaped in response to the burgeoning pet class. The presence of beloved animals in the home led to a number of welfare-minded political movements, inspired in part by the Darwinian thought that began to sprout at the time. Nineteenth-century animals may not have been the heroes of their own lives but, as Kreilkamp shows, the history of domestic pets deeply influenced the history of the English novel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAnimals in literature. 0aEnglish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHuman-animal relationships in literature. 0aPets in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aEngland.  aVictorian fiction.  aanimals.  aanthropocentrism.  adomestic.  adomestication.  apets.  athe novel.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226576404423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226576404/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles